          <h2>How a hallway conversation became a <em>cooperative.</em></h2>
          <nav class="toc">
            <a href="#chapter-1"><span class="num">01</span> The conversation that kept happening</a>
            <a href="#chapter-2"><span class="num">02</span> The first deal</a>
            <a href="#chapter-3"><span class="num">03</span> A council, not a company</a>
            <a href="#chapter-4"><span class="num">04</span> The Hall of Fame</a>
          </nav>
        </aside>
        <div class="body">
          <p id="chapter-1">
            <span class="placeholder placeholder-inline">[Brodsky and Greenberg]</span> didn&rsquo;t set out to start a cooperative. They were independent CAM company owners running healthy regional firms &mdash; and they kept ending up in the same hallway conversation at industry events. It was always the same shape: the nationals had vendor terms the independents couldn&rsquo;t match, boards were getting price-sensitive, and the loneliest seat at every operator&rsquo;s table was the one labelled <em>owner</em>.
          </p>
          <p>
            What changed was that one year, instead of going back to their separate companies and absorbing the cost, they stayed in the hallway. They walked the conversation into a side room. They invited <span class="placeholder placeholder-inline">[#]</span> other operators they trusted. The agenda for that first meeting was, in its entirety: <em>what would it look like if we negotiated together?</em>
          </p>

          <h3 id="chapter-2">The first deal</h3>
          <p>
            The first thing the group negotiated together was banking. <span class="placeholder placeholder-inline">[Brief description of the founding banking program &mdash; partner bank, the structure, the terms it unlocked for member companies.]</span> The deal was small in dollar terms, but the proof was the shape of it: pricing only available because the firms showed up as a group.
          </p>
          <p>
            The second was software. The third was a Wednesday afternoon &mdash; four hours over coffee &mdash; that turned into the peer council the cooperative is now built around. The pattern was clear: pool the volume, share the intelligence, keep the independence.
          </p>
          <p class="pull">
            We weren&rsquo;t trying to build an organization. We were trying to keep a room going. The cooperative is what it took to keep the room going.
            <cite>&mdash; <span class="placeholder placeholder-inline">[Brodsky]</span>, on the founding</cite>
          </p>

          <h3 id="chapter-3">A council, not a company</h3>
          <p>
            From the beginning, <span class="placeholder placeholder-inline">[Brodsky]</span> and <span class="placeholder placeholder-inline">[Greenberg]</span> insisted on the same thing: the cooperative wasn&rsquo;t a holding company, a franchise, or a buying agency. It was a council of owner-operators that happened to share back-end leverage. One company, one vote. Membership by introduction only. Vendors that earned the lineup by member-rated performance, and defended their slot each year.
          </p>
          <p>
            They wrote those rules down in a way that has barely needed editing since. Innovia today still admits members by nomination, still routes every cooperative-wide decision through a one-company-one-vote, and still won&rsquo;t take a vendor fee to feature a partner. The structure the two of them drafted is what every member company joins.
          </p>

          <h3 id="chapter-4">The Hall of Fame</h3>
          <p>
            In <span class="placeholder placeholder-inline">[year]</span>, the Cooperative Hall of Fame inducted <span class="placeholder placeholder-inline">[Brodsky and Greenberg]</span> for their work building one of the first member-owned cooperatives in the community association management industry. The induction citation, in part: <em><span class="placeholder placeholder-inline">[brief excerpt from the citation, e.g. &ldquo;for demonstrating that independent operators could compete with consolidated capital without surrendering their independence.&rdquo;]</span></em>
          </p>
          <p>
            The cooperative they started has grown to <span>80+</span> member companies across <span>25+</span> states, managing more than <span>1.4 million</span> households. The roster of inductees, alongside the founders, is below.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

